---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import PrivateHeader from "../../components/PrivateHeader.astro";
import CTA from "../../components/CTA.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout noindex={true} title="The Case for Fractional Executive Support | Leigh-Ann Martin" description="Research, statistics, and data on fractional executive assistant services, market trends, cost analysis, and ROI.">
  <PrivateHeader />
  <main>
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="bg-primary pt-28 pb-16 md:pt-36 md:pb-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-secondary mb-4">Research</p>
        <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl text-white leading-tight mb-6">
          The Case for Fractional Executive Support
        </h1>
        <p class="text-white/55 text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto">
          Market data, cost analysis, productivity research, and industry trends. Everything you need to make a data-driven decision about executive operations support.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Market Overview -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 1</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">The Fractional Executive Market</h2>

        <div class="prose-custom space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>The global fractional executive market was valued at <strong class="text-primary">$9.4 billion in 2025</strong> and is projected to reach $24.7 billion by 2034, expanding at a compound annual growth rate of 11.3%.<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="text-secondary">1</a></sup> An alternative valuation puts the market at $5.7 billion, growing at a 14% CAGR.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="text-secondary">2</a></sup></p>

          <p>Adoption is accelerating. <strong class="text-primary">25% of US businesses</strong> currently use fractional hiring, with projections of 35% by the end of 2026.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="text-secondary">2</a></sup> The demand for fractional executives doubled from 60,000 roles in 2022 to 120,000 in 2024, representing 46% year-over-year growth.<sup><a href="#ref-3" class="text-secondary">3</a></sup></p>

          <p>North America leads the market, commanding <strong class="text-primary">$4.1 billion (43.7%)</strong> of global market value in 2025.<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="text-secondary">1</a></sup> And 68% more companies are hiring fractional executives in 2025 compared to the prior year.<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="text-secondary">2</a></sup></p>

          <p>The broader gig economy provides context: more than <strong class="text-primary">70 million Americans</strong> (approximately 36% of the total workforce) are estimated to be part of the gig economy in 2025.<sup><a href="#ref-4" class="text-secondary">4</a></sup></p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mt-8">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm text-center">
            <p class="font-serif text-3xl text-secondary">$9.4B</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Global market value (2025)<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="text-secondary">1</a></sup></p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm text-center">
            <p class="font-serif text-3xl text-secondary">11.3%</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Compound annual growth<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="text-secondary">1</a></sup></p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-5 shadow-sm text-center">
            <p class="font-serif text-3xl text-secondary">68%</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">More companies hiring fractional YoY<sup><a href="#ref-2" class="text-secondary">2</a></sup></p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- The CEO Time Problem -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 2</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">The CEO Time Problem</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>A landmark Harvard Business School study by Michael Porter and Nitin Nohria tracked <strong class="text-primary">60,000 hours of CEO time</strong> across 27 executives and found that the average CEO works 62.5 hours per week, spending 72% of that time in meetings.<sup><a href="#ref-5" class="text-secondary">5</a></sup> The study, which won the HBR McKinsey Award, revealed that CEOs attend an average of <strong class="text-primary">37 meetings per week</strong>, with formal reviews alone consuming a quarter of total work time.<sup><a href="#ref-5" class="text-secondary">5</a></sup></p>

          <p>Research indicates that <strong class="text-primary">upwards of 30% of a CEO's working hours</strong> are typically devoted to tasks that could be outsourced to a qualified assistant.<sup><a href="#ref-6" class="text-secondary">6</a></sup> Most CEOs spend over 20 hours weekly on tasks that pull focus from strategic priorities.<sup><a href="#ref-6" class="text-secondary">6</a></sup></p>

          <p>The specific time drains break down as follows:<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 mt-6 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-serif text-2xl text-secondary">10-12 hrs</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Meeting prep and follow-up per week<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-serif text-2xl text-secondary">6-8 hrs</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Calendar coordination and conflict resolution<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-serif text-2xl text-secondary">4-6 hrs</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Email triage and templating<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-serif text-2xl text-secondary">3-4 hrs</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs mt-1">Travel booking and itinerary changes<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed space-y-4">
          <p>A separate study found that <strong class="text-primary">75.5% of executives</strong> identified calendar management as their highest-impact productivity driver, outperforming email and meeting support by nearly 2x.<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>

          <p>Case studies show that hiring a fractional executive assistant can reclaim <strong class="text-primary">10-14 hours per week</strong> while cutting meetings by 25%.<sup><a href="#ref-7" class="text-secondary">7</a></sup></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Cost Analysis -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 3</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">Fractional vs. Full-Time: The Cost Analysis</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>The fractional executive model delivers <strong class="text-primary">cost-efficiency advantages of 40% to 70%</strong> versus full-time C-suite hires. More specifically, fractional models charge only for the hours or projects needed, reducing costs by 50-70%.<sup><a href="#ref-3" class="text-secondary">3</a></sup></p>

          <p>When you add employer-side costs to a full-time hire, the true cost runs <strong class="text-primary">25-35% above base salary</strong> for taxes, benefits, training, and ongoing management.<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="text-secondary">8</a></sup> Recruiting costs alone average 33%+ of first-year salary.<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="text-secondary">8</a></sup></p>

          <p>Average EA tenure is <strong class="text-primary">2-3 years</strong>, meaning you face repeated recruiting cycles.<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="text-secondary">8</a></sup> A bad hire at the executive assistant level costs 6+ months of operational disruption.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-8 mb-6">
          <table class="w-full text-sm bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-primary/5">
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-4 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Cost Category</th>
                <th class="text-right text-primary font-semibold p-4 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Full-Time EA (NYC)</th>
                <th class="text-right text-secondary font-semibold p-4 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Fractional Partner</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-text-muted">
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Base salary</td><td class="text-right p-4">$120,000 - $165,000</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary font-medium">$60,000 - $150,000</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Benefits (28% of base)<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="text-secondary">8</a></sup></td><td class="text-right p-4">$33,600 - $46,200</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary font-medium">$0</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Recruiting (33% of Year 1)<sup><a href="#ref-8" class="text-secondary">8</a></sup></td><td class="text-right p-4">$39,600 - $54,450</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary font-medium">$0</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Ramp-up productivity loss</td><td class="text-right p-4">3-6 months</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary font-medium">30 days or less</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Turnover risk (annualized)</td><td class="text-right p-4">$15,000 - $25,000</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary font-medium">Month-to-month</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06] bg-primary/5 font-semibold"><td class="p-4 text-primary">Total Year 1 Cost</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-primary">$208,000 - $290,000+</td><td class="text-right p-4 text-secondary">$60,000 - $150,000</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p><strong class="text-primary">74% of companies report lower risk</strong> with fractional vs. full-time executive hires.<sup><a href="#ref-9" class="text-secondary">9</a></sup> Fractional executives deliver higher ROI because they bring years of industry knowledge, execute faster, avoid costly mistakes, and provide targeted solutions without a lengthy learning curve.<sup><a href="#ref-3" class="text-secondary">3</a></sup></p>

          <p>The return on investment for fractional EA support is estimated at <strong class="text-primary">3-5x</strong>, with 3-5 hours of reclaimed executive work for every dollar spent.<sup><a href="#ref-10" class="text-secondary">10</a></sup></p>
        </div>

        <div class="mt-6 text-center">
          <a href={`${base}tools/fractional-vs-fulltime`} class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-secondary text-sm font-semibold hover:underline">
            Calculate your specific comparison
            <svg class="w-3.5 h-3.5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- EA Market in NYC -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 4</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">The Executive Assistant Market in NYC</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>There are currently <strong class="text-primary">755+ open EA positions</strong> in NYC on Glassdoor alone, with a 12% increase in job listings year-over-year, especially in tech and finance.<sup><a href="#ref-11" class="text-secondary">11</a></sup></p>

          <p>Compensation continues to climb as the talent pool shrinks. CEOs are asking more of their support staff, yet the pool of qualified professionals is getting smaller.<sup><a href="#ref-11" class="text-secondary">11</a></sup></p>
        </div>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto mt-8 mb-6">
          <table class="w-full text-sm bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm overflow-hidden">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-primary/5">
                <th class="text-left text-primary font-semibold p-4 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Industry</th>
                <th class="text-right text-primary font-semibold p-4 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide">Median Total Pay (NYC)</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-text-muted">
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4 font-medium text-primary">Financial Services</td><td class="text-right p-4">$113,133</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Pharmaceutical & Biotech</td><td class="text-right p-4">$109,760</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Information Technology</td><td class="text-right p-4">$107,741</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Legal</td><td class="text-right p-4">$104,559</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-t border-primary/[0.06]"><td class="p-4">Real Estate</td><td class="text-right p-4">$102,364</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-xs italic">Source: Glassdoor NYC EA Salary Data, 2026, based on 10,496 reported salaries.<sup><a href="#ref-12" class="text-secondary">12</a></sup></p>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed mt-6">
          <p>The workplace structure is shifting: <strong class="text-primary">55-60% of EA roles</strong> are hybrid (3 days in-office), 30% are fully in-office (especially in finance, legal, and healthcare), and only 10-15% are fully remote.<sup><a href="#ref-11" class="text-secondary">11</a></sup></p>

          <p>Remote EA positions have increased 25% year-over-year.<sup><a href="#ref-11" class="text-secondary">11</a></sup></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Board Governance -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 5</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">Board Governance: Where Preparation Meets Credibility</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>Board directors spend an average of <strong class="text-primary">278 hours annually</strong> on board activities, a large portion of which is preparing for and attending meetings.<sup><a href="#ref-13" class="text-secondary">13</a></sup> Governance teams spend approximately 10 hours per meeting on minute-taking alone, while agendas and board materials often take hundreds of hours to prepare.<sup><a href="#ref-13" class="text-secondary">13</a></sup></p>

          <p>Best practice dictates that directors should receive board packs at least one week in advance. However, <strong class="text-primary">55% of directors receive materials</strong> (often running over 200 pages) less than five days before meetings.<sup><a href="#ref-13" class="text-secondary">13</a></sup></p>

          <p>According to NACD's Board Practices and Oversight Survey, only <strong class="text-primary">13% of directors</strong> rate their board packs as "extremely effective."<sup><a href="#ref-14" class="text-secondary">14</a></sup> This represents a massive gap between governance best practice and execution reality.</p>

          <p>The implication is clear: companies that invest in professional board prep infrastructure gain a measurable governance advantage. When board materials arrive on time, are well-organized, and include actionable context, meetings become strategic instead of reactive.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- AI and the EA Role -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-bold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Section 6</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-8">AI and the Future of Executive Support</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>The 2026 executive assistant is expected to be more than a coordinator. Employers are increasingly looking for:<sup><a href="#ref-15" class="text-secondary">15</a></sup></p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3 my-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-1">AI-fluent professionals</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Who can use Claude, ChatGPT, or Copilot to draft communications, summarize documents, and automate repetitive tasks.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-1">Data-literate support</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Who can pull reports, create dashboards, and present findings to leadership teams.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl p-4 shadow-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-primary text-sm mb-1">Strategic thinkers</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Who can take on project management, process improvement, and operational efficiency beyond scheduling.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4 text-text-muted text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
          <p><strong class="text-primary">27% of AI users save over 9 hours per week</strong>, with average time savings of 1.5 to 2.5 hours per week across all users.<sup><a href="#ref-16" class="text-secondary">16</a></sup> AI coding and productivity tools deliver 26-55% improvements for experienced practitioners.<sup><a href="#ref-16" class="text-secondary">16</a></sup></p>

          <p><strong class="text-primary">62% of organizations</strong> are already experimenting with AI agents, indicating widespread early-stage adoption.<sup><a href="#ref-16" class="text-secondary">16</a></sup> For executive support, this means the EAs who adopted AI tools early (2024-2025) have a significant advantage over those still learning.</p>

          <p>The convergence is clear: the most effective fractional executive partners in 2026 are those who combine deep C-suite operational experience with AI fluency. They deliver faster draft preparation, more thorough stakeholder research, and better-organized board materials, all at a fraction of the time it would take manually.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Key Takeaways -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-primary">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="text-center mb-10">
          <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-white">Key Takeaways</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/[0.08] rounded-xl p-5 flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-secondary font-serif text-xl font-bold mt-0.5">1</span>
            <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">The fractional executive market is growing at 11-14% annually. This is not a trend. It's a structural shift in how companies access leadership-level talent.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/[0.08] rounded-xl p-5 flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-secondary font-serif text-xl font-bold mt-0.5">2</span>
            <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">CEOs spend 20+ hours per week on tasks that could be delegated. That's 30% of their working life on operations instead of strategy.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/[0.08] rounded-xl p-5 flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-secondary font-serif text-xl font-bold mt-0.5">3</span>
            <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">Full-time EA hires cost 40-70% more than fractional partners when you include benefits, recruiting, ramp-up, and turnover risk.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/[0.08] rounded-xl p-5 flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-secondary font-serif text-xl font-bold mt-0.5">4</span>
            <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">55% of board directors receive their materials less than 5 days before meetings. Only 13% rate their board packs as "extremely effective." Professional board prep is a governance advantage.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/[0.08] rounded-xl p-5 flex items-start gap-4">
            <span class="text-secondary font-serif text-xl font-bold mt-0.5">5</span>
            <p class="text-white/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">AI-fluent EAs who adopted tools like Claude in 2024 are 1-2 years ahead of most candidates. This advantage compounds: 40% faster draft preparation translates directly into more strategic work delivered per dollar.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- References -->
    <section class="py-16 md:py-24 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl text-primary mb-8">Sources & References</h2>

        <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-text-muted leading-relaxed list-decimal list-inside">
          <li id="ref-1"><a href="https://dataintelo.com/report/fractional-executiveplace-market" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">Dataintelo, "Fractional Executive Marketplace Market Research Report 2034."</a> Global market valued at $9.4B in 2025, projected $24.7B by 2034 (11.3% CAGR). North America at $4.1B (43.7% share).</li>
          <li id="ref-2"><a href="https://fractionus.com/blog/10-statistics-fractional-work-future" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">Fractionus, "10 Statistics That Prove Fractional Work Is the Future."</a> Market at $5.7B, 14% CAGR. 25% of US businesses use fractional hiring; 68% YoY increase.</li>
          <li id="ref-3"><a href="https://fractional-csuite.com/resources/future-of-work/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">Fractional C-Suite, "The Future of Work: Why Fractional Executives Are Booming in the AI Era."</a> Demand doubled 2022-2024. Cost savings of 40-70% vs. full-time.</li>
          <li id="ref-4"><a href="https://carry.com/learn/gig-economy-trends-for-freelancers-and-self-employed-workers" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">Carry, "2026 Gig Economy Trends for Freelancers and Self-Employed Workers."</a> 70M+ Americans in gig economy (36% of workforce).</li>
          <li id="ref-5"><a href="https://hbr.org/2025/05/how-ceos-should-manage-their-time" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">Porter, M.E. & Nohria, N., "How CEOs Manage Time," Harvard Business Review.</a> 60,000 hours tracked, 27 CEOs. 62.5 hrs/week, 72% in meetings, 37 meetings/week. HBR McKinsey Award winner.</li>
          <li id="ref-6"><a href="https://blog.belaysolutions.com/when-should-a-ceo-hire-an-executive-assistant" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">BELAY Solutions, "When Should a CEO Hire an Executive Assistant?"</a> 30%+ of CEO hours on delegable tasks. 20+ hours/week on non-strategic work.</li>
          <li id="ref-7"><a href="https://www.workmate.com/blog/case-study-how-an-executive-assistant-saved-10-hours-per-week" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">WorkMate, "How an Executive Assistant Saved 10+ Hours per Week."</a> Time drain breakdown by category. 75.5% identify calendar mgmt as highest-impact driver. 10-14 hrs/week reclaimed.</li>
          <li id="ref-8"><a href="https://proassisting.com/resources/articles/fractional-assistants-save-time-money/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-secondary hover:underline">ProAssisting, "What's the Typical ROI of Outsourcing EA Tasks for Founders?"</a> 25-35% overhead above base salary. Recruiting at 33%+ of Year 1 salary. EA tenure 2-3 years.</li>
